## API Design Review for Plan [PLAN_NUMBER]

### Phase 1: REST Conventions

**Q1.1: Resource naming and HTTP semantics**

| Endpoint | HTTP Method | Resource Semantics | Idempotent? | Safe? |
|----------|-------------|-------------------|-------------|-------|
| | | | | |

- [ ] Resources use nouns (e.g., `/orders`, `/users`), not verbs
- [ ] HTTP methods are used correctly (GET read, POST create, PUT replace, PATCH partial update, DELETE remove)
- [ ] GET and HEAD are safe; GET, PUT, DELETE are idempotent
- [ ] No action verbs in URLs (e.g., avoid `/getOrder`, prefer `GET /orders/{id}`)

**Q1.2: URL structure**

- [ ] Hierarchical relationships are clear (e.g., `/orders/{id}/items`)
- [ ] No deep nesting beyond 3 levels (e.g., `/a/{id}/b/{id}/c` is too deep)
- [ ] Plural nouns for collections (e.g., `/orders` not `/order`)
- [ ] Lowercase, hyphen-separated URLs (e.g., `/order-items`)

---

### Phase 2: Versioning

**Q2.1: Version strategy**

| Strategy | Chosen? | Rationale |
|----------|---------|-----------|
| URL path (e.g., `/v1/orders`) | | |
| Header (e.g., `Accept: application/vnd.api+json;version=1`) | | |
| Query parameter (e.g., `?version=1`) | | |

- [ ] Versioning strategy is explicit and documented
- [ ] Default version behavior is defined when no version specified
- [ ] Version deprecation timeline is communicated

**Q2.2: Version lifecycle**

- [ ] Breaking changes require new major version
- [ ] Additive changes are backward compatible within same version
- [ ] Sunset header or deprecation notice for deprecated versions

---

### Phase 3: Pagination

**Q3.1: Pagination pattern**

| Pattern | Used? | Cursor/Offset? | Metadata Included? |
|---------|-------|----------------|-------------------|
| Cursor-based | | | |
| Offset-based | | | |

- [ ] All list endpoints support pagination (default page size documented)
- [ ] Response includes pagination metadata (next cursor, total count if applicable)
- [ ] Maximum page size is enforced to prevent abuse
- [ ] Cursor format is opaque and stable (e.g., base64-encoded)

**Q3.2: Pagination response shape**

```json
{
  "data": [...],
  "meta": {
    "next_cursor": "eyJpZCI6MTAwfQ==",
    "has_more": true,
    "page_size": 20
  }
}
```

- [ ] Consistent structure across all list endpoints
- [ ] Cursor is stable across page boundaries (no race conditions)

---

### Phase 4: Error Responses

**Q4.1: Error format**

- [ ] Errors follow RFC 7807 Problem Details or equivalent structured format
- [ ] Error responses include: type, title, status, detail, instance, trace_id
- [ ] Machine-readable error codes for client handling
- [ ] Human-readable messages for debugging
- [ ] No stack traces or sensitive data in production responses

**Q4.2: HTTP status mapping**

| Scenario | HTTP Status | Error Code |
|----------|-------------|------------|
| Validation failure | 400 | VALIDATION_ERROR |
| Unauthorized | 401 | UNAUTHORIZED |
| Forbidden | 403 | FORBIDDEN |
| Not found | 404 | NOT_FOUND |
| Conflict | 409 | CONFLICT |
| Rate limited | 429 | RATE_LIMITED |
| Server error | 500 | INTERNAL_ERROR |

---

### Phase 5: Rate Limiting

**Q5.1: Rate limit design**

- [ ] Rate limits are defined per endpoint or per resource
- [ ] Response headers include: `X-RateLimit-Limit`, `X-RateLimit-Remaining`, `X-RateLimit-Reset`
- [ ] 429 responses include `Retry-After` header
- [ ] Rate limit tiers are documented (e.g., free vs paid tier)

**Q5.2: Client guidance**

- [ ] Documentation explains how to handle 429 responses
- [ ] Exponential backoff or retry-after guidance provided
- [ ] Bulk endpoints have separate limits from single-item endpoints

---

### Phase 6: Security Headers

**Q6.1: Required headers**

| Header | Purpose | Present? |
|--------|---------|-----------|
| Content-Type | Request/response format | |
| Authorization | Bearer token or API key | |
| X-Request-ID | Request correlation | |
| X-Correlation-ID | Cross-service tracing | |

**Q6.2: Security considerations**

- [ ] Authentication required for all non-public endpoints
- [ ] Authorization checks (e.g., RBAC) per resource
- [ ] Input validation on all request bodies and query params
- [ ] No sensitive data in URLs (use POST body for secrets)
- [ ] CORS configured if browser-based

---

### Phase 7: Documentation

**Q7.1: OpenAPI completeness**

- [ ] All endpoints documented in OpenAPI 3.x spec
- [ ] Request/response schemas defined
- [ ] Error responses documented
- [ ] Authentication scheme documented
- [ ] Examples provided for each endpoint

**Q7.2: Developer experience**

- [ ] Quick start guide available
- [ ] SDK or code samples for common languages
- [ ] Changelog or version history maintained
- [ ] Postman/Insomnia collection or equivalent

---

## Review Decision Matrix

| Category | Pass | Modify | Block |
|----------|------|--------|-------|
| REST conventions | Correct semantics | Minor inconsistencies | Wrong HTTP usage |
| Versioning | Strategy clear | Needs documentation | No versioning plan |
| Pagination | Consistent pattern | Gaps in metadata | No pagination |
| Error responses | RFC 7807 compliant | Partial structure | Unstructured errors |
| Rate limiting | Headers present | Incomplete headers | No rate limit |
| Security headers | All required | Minor gaps | Auth/validation missing |
| Documentation | Complete | Gaps identified | Missing spec |

